  1. In terms of price, which neighborhood has the highest standard deviation?
    1. StoneBr <-
    2. Timber
    3. Veenker
    4. NridgHt 
# type your code for Question 3 here, and Knit
ames_train %>% 
  select(Neighborhood, price) %>% 
  group_by(Neighborhood) %>% 
  summarise(avg = mean(price, na.rm=TRUE), std = sd(price, na.rm=TRUE)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(std))

# type your code for Question 9 here, and Knit
# lambda = 3, std = 1
# k = (lambda/std)^2, theta = std^2/lambda
# k_star = k + sum(xi)
# theta_star = theta/(n*theta + 1)
lambda <- 3
std <- 1

k <- (lambda/std)^2
theta <- std^2/lambda

c(k, theta)
## [1] 9.0000000 0.3333333
sum_x <- ames_train %>% 
  filter(area > 2000) %>%
  summarise(sum_x = sum(Bedroom.AbvGr))

n <- ames_train %>% 
  filter(area > 2000) %>%
  summarise(n = n())

k_star <- k + sum_x
theta_star = theta/(n*theta+1)

c(sum_x, n, k_star, theta_star)
## $sum_x
## [1] 501
## 
## $n
## [1] 138

## $sum_x
## [1] 510
## 
## $n
## [1] 0.007092199
lambda_star <- k_star*theta_star
std_star = theta_star*sqrt(k_star)

# type your code for Question 10 here, and Knit
# outliers obtained from plot
lm_q10 = lm(log(price) ~ log(area), data = ames_train)
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(lm_q10)

# find outliers by setting threshold of R_squared at the (n-3)th biggest R_squared
rsquared_q10 = resid(lm_q10)**2
threshold = sort(rsquared_q10, partial=(1000-3))[997]
which(rsquared_q10 > threshold)
